    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Daisy  by: </span>
      Amy Henry
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=russia-ussr">russia-ussr</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=finland">finland</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=eastern-europe">eastern-europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=to-re-read">to-re-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=estonia">estonia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013908-daisy?shelf=favorites-2nd-place">favorites-2nd-place</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer104229420" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10599376463590956359">Flies: a recurring theme. I mean presence. Character?<br/><br/>Interesting to grow to dislike the main character, Aliide, the more I read. The very end though has me stumped. Am I stupid? Did I miss something or is that last section unnecessary?<br/><br/>I didn&apos;t learn that much even though I&apos;ve never read anything about Estonia before. I have read lots of Russian and Soviet stuff so some of that &quot;tension&quot; is familiar, all that not-knowing-who-you-can-trust stuff. I did love the details like horseradish in pickles </span>
  <span id="freeText10599376463590956359" style="display:none">Flies: a recurring theme. I mean presence. Character?<br /><br />Interesting to grow to dislike the main character, Aliide, the more I read. The very end though has me stumped. Am I stupid? Did I miss something or is that last section unnecessary?<br /><br />I didn't learn that much even though I've never read anything about Estonia before. I have read lots of Russian and Soviet stuff so some of that "tension" is familiar, all that not-knowing-who-you-can-trust stuff. I did love the details like horseradish in pickles and marigold salve, things that Ingel and Aliide make.<br /><br />Is Aliide's love of Hans obsessive or heroic? Is what she did to Ingel evil and selfish or heroic (I just thought of that)?<br /><br />I only noticed the word "purge" once and it had to do with cleaning a face. Wait, I should maybe look at that more closely.<br /><br />The parallels between Aliide and Zara (A to Z) are interesting. I read in other reviews about how shame is a theme. Yup, it is. Shame and loyalty and saving yourself and saving others. <br /><br />It unfolds in time jumps and flashbacks which are cleverly built, but makes it hard for me to remember when stuff happened now that I'm trying to reconstruct it here.<br /><br />I liked this story a lot. Amy Henry gave it to me. I passed it on to Lisa Hayden. And then I missed it so much I bought it again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10599376463590956359" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


