  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_225696066" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/225696066" />
    <a title="Matti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6734065-matti"><img alt="Matti" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/225696066?book_show_action=true">Oct 20, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matti" href="/user/show/6734065-matti">Matti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer225696066" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11695058094785425073">This is propably the most hyped book in Finland since the days of Väinö Linna and Mika Waltari. For me, it was rather hard to understand why.<br/><br/>To give a short introduction on the many problems this book had: first, the writer made the basic mistake of all mediocre writers, which is to explain too much. I am talking, of course, about the psychological explanations with the characters. Its amazing how much you can explain the character&apos;s behavior without actually giving the character any depth. Some</span>
  <span id="freeText11695058094785425073" style="display:none">This is propably the most hyped book in Finland since the days of Väinö Linna and Mika Waltari. For me, it was rather hard to understand why.<br /><br />To give a short introduction on the many problems this book had: first, the writer made the basic mistake of all mediocre writers, which is to explain too much. I am talking, of course, about the psychological explanations with the characters. Its amazing how much you can explain the character's behavior without actually giving the character any depth. Some books can manage such explanations with style, though (I'm thinking of, for example, Milan Kundera's books), but not this one.<br /><br />I can't say much about the plot since I didn't finish the book (I read it about halfway through before giving it up). As far as I read, the plot was uninterresting and you could see everything coming. We all know communists were bastards, so nothing new there. We all know there are women who are treated badly in the world today. Its a shame, yes, but it is not yet a storyline. If you have nothing else to say, you could just as well write a letter to the newspaper instead of writing a novel. Unlike Väinö Linna, for example, whose books gave a whole new interpretation of history and the people involved in the turns of history, this one does the exact opposite: it portrays women in history in a way we all know is fashionable and trendy (which is probably why this book sells).<br /><br />All in all, to say that this book belongs to the same canon of great Finnish books such as those of Linna and Waltari is an overstatement. It might have some value as an historical novel or as a novel discussing women's sex slavery, yes, but even so it offers nothing new to either one of these subjects.<br /><br />But then again, like said, I only read it halfway through, so I might be wrong. But a good book is interresting by the time it reaches the halfway mark and this one wasn't, so I stand behind my rating.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11695058094785425073" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

